From: tawc
Origin: own

Zero the vulkan_info.device_id in the kumquat server's
RESOURCE_CREATE_BLOB response so the chroot-side
VirtGpuKumquatResource::createMapping takes its plain-mmap branch
(virtgpu_kumquat_resource_map) instead of the GfxStreamVulkanMapper
path.

The mapper path is what canonical gfxstream deployments use: the
chroot's Mesa-radv (or other "real" Vulkan ICD that matches the
host GPU UUID) imports the exported dmabuf via VkImportMemoryFdInfoKHR
into a VkDeviceMemory and maps it. Our chroot only has
libvulkan_gfxstream.so as the ICD, so the mapper recursively picks
gfxstream-vk for the import. gfxstream-vk's importDmabuf path calls
kumquat's resource_import, which expects an "emulated" handle
(a SHM whose first 4 bytes encode a resource_id). Our hook now
ships a real dmabuf fd whose first 4 bytes are typically zero, so
resource_import reads back resource_handle=0 and the subsequent
vkAllocateMemory(VkImportColorBufferGOOGLE{colorBuffer=0}) trips
the host's `vk_decoder_global_state.cpp(5853) Failed to get
allocation info for ColorBuffer:0` abort.

With device_uuid all-zero in the response, createMapping skips the
mapper and just mmaps the dmabuf fd directly — which is exactly
what we want, since our hook gives the chroot a real, mmap-able fd
that aliases the AHB's underlying pages. See notes/gfxstream-bridge.md
"WSI plan" for the surrounding design.

